Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Remove the @puff pastry sheet{3/4%pack} from your fridge to allow it to come up to room temperature.

Thinly slice the @portobello mushrooms{4}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Add the mushrooms to the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until golden, ~{6-8%minutes}, then remove from the heat. Add a drizzle of @oil{} if needed.

Once cooked, allow the mushrooms to cool slightly, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop them onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

In the meantime, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the parsley, @cream cheese{100%grams}, @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%grams} and half the garlic. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Lay your pastry sheet on a large baking tray with its baking paper beneath.

Spoon the cream cheese mixture down one side, leaving a 2cm border. Top with the cooled mushrooms and drizzle over the @fig jam{40%grams}.

Fold the pastry over the filling to enclose it, gently pressing down the edges with the back of a #fork{} to seal the 3 open sides. Poke 3 holes along the top with a sharp knife.

> Brush the top of the pastry with a little milk if you have some.

Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until golden, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @Brussels sprouts{200%grams} and halve through the root.

Wipe out the (now empty) frying pan and pop on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. When hot, add the sprouts to the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir-fry until starting to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the remaining @garlic clove{1}(grated) and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}.

Allow to cook until the sprouts are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}, then stir in the @butter{20%grams}. Remove from the heat.

Combine the @wild mushroom paste{15%grams} and @water for the sauce{125%ml} in a #small saucepan{}.

Bring to the boil, stir and lower the heat so the sauce simmers gently. Cook for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{75%grams} until combined, then remove from the heat.

When your Wellington is cooked, remove from the oven and allow to rest for a few mins.

When everything's ready, sprinkle the @truffle zest{1%sachet} over the potatoes.

Slice your mushroom Wellington in half widthways and share between your #plates{}.

Serve the sprouts and truffle potatoes alongside and spoon the creamy wild mushroom sauce over to finish. Enjoy!